data.content:
In .NET 10 (starting with .NET 9 SR10+), `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was deprecated on Android because the underlying `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` flag was removed by Google.

The recommended replacement is to use **keyboard insets** via the new `KeyboardInsets` API or handle it manually with Android's `WindowInsetsCompat`. Here's the practical fix:

**Option 1 – Use `android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize"` + edge-to-edge insets (preferred)**

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
[Activity(WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustResize, ...)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

Then in your layout, wrap your input bar in a container that respects safe-area/keyboard insets. In your page XAML:

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ... />
    <Entry Grid.Row="1" Placeholder="Type a message..."
           Margin="{OnPlatform Android='0,0,0,0'}" />
</Grid>
```

And in `MauiProgram.cs`, enable edge-to-edge handling:

```csharp
builder.ConfigureMauiHandlers(handlers =>
{
#if ANDROID
    Microsoft.Maui.ApplicationModel.Platform.ActivityStateChanged += (s, e) =>
    {
        if (e.State == ActivityState.Created)
        {
            AndroidX.Core.View.ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(
                e.Activity.Window.DecorView, new InsetListener());
        }
    };
#endif
});
```

**Option 2 – Simplest workaround using `IKeyboardInsets` (.NET 10)**

If you're on .NET 10 Preview 4+, use the new built-in support:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
builder.UseMauiApp<App>()
       .ConfigureEssentials(essentials =>
       {
           essentials.AddKeyboardInsets();
       });
```

Then in your page code-behind or ViewModel, subscribe to inset changes and adjust your bottom padding:

```csharp
KeyboardInsets.Current.InsetsChanged += (s, insets) =>
{
    InputBar.Margin = new Thickness(0, 0, 0, insets.Bottom);
};
```

---

**Quick fix if you just need it working now:** Set `AdjustResize` in the Activity attribute (Option 1) — it still works on most Android versions despite the deprecation warning. It only fully breaks on Android 15+ with edge-to-edge enforced, at which point you'll need the insets approach.

For iOS, `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` handles this automatically in .NET 10 MAUI — no extra work needed.
